@flexiarg peeragogy/roles
@title Treat Roles as Held, Not Owned — and Watch Them Shift
@keywords roles, autodidact, tutor, tutee, role-fluidity, default-roles, role-shift
@audience peer-learning practitioners, facilitators
@tone reflective
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/carrying-capacity peeragogy/moderation]

! conclusion: Educational interactions inherit roles by default — autodidact, tutor, tutee, and outward into librarian, editor, administrator, and beyond.  The pattern is to treat these roles as *held* rather than *owned*: a participant occupies a role at a moment, and the same person may shift roles as the activity changes.  Naming roles makes coordination cheaper; treating them as fixed identities makes the group rigid.
  + context: Peer-learning starts from the autodidact and bifurcates outward; even a single learner traverses several roles in the course of one project (asking questions, answering them, checking proofs, fetching resources).  In group contexts, roles multiply: tutor, tutee, parent-figure, principal, librarian, technician, editor, policy-maker, partner.  The handbook notes that decomposing learning into roles could be an endless theoretical task; the practical observation is that roles are present by default at the start of an interaction and that they may shift as the work develops.  The pattern is to keep that fluidity available rather than letting initial role-assignments harden into permanent identities.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: role legibility ↔ role mobility.
    Real: named roles let the group coordinate and let newcomers find their footing.  But the same names can lock participants into identities they would otherwise outgrow — the "newcomer" who never gets to facilitate, the "facilitator" who never gets to learn from a beginner.
    Irreducible: a role cannot simultaneously be stable enough to coordinate around and fluid enough to permit unrestricted shift.  Every role-naming choice is balancing these two.
    Active: the pull recurs at every transition — a tutee who begins to teach, a facilitator who needs to step back, a contributor who picks up a wrapping role for one cycle.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Name roles, not identities: when a role is assigned (heartbeat-keeper, wrapper, moderator), name the role and its scope, not "X is the type of person who does this."  The role is a hat someone is wearing this week.
    (2) Default-role audit: at intervals, ask which default roles the group has inherited from how it started, and whether they still fit.  Roles that made sense at convening time may not fit at maturity.
    (3) Role rotation: where a role is sustainable but heavy (heartbeat-keeper, wrapper, moderator), build in rotation rather than assigning indefinitely.  Spreads cost, prevents identity-lock, builds redundancy.
    (4) Role-shift announcement: when a participant changes role — newcomer becoming editor, facilitator stepping back — the change is named explicitly to the group, both to coordinate practical handoff and to model that role-shift is normal.
    (5) Multiple roles per person: a single contributor may hold several roles concurrently (editor + heartbeat-keeper) and that is fine, as long as the carrying capacity (peeragogy/carrying-capacity) of each role-holder is respected.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: roles in the group are nameable on demand, role-shifts happen visibly and without drama, and the same person can occupy different roles at different times without that being remarked as exceptional.  Failing when: roles harden into identities, role-shifts are perceived as betrayals or promotions, or a role becomes single-occupancy permanently with no successor.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Identity ossification: a participant becomes "the X person" and finds it costly to do anything else, even when they want to.
    - Single-point-of-failure roles: critical functions depend on one specific person with no shared name for the role they occupy.
    - Role-name absence: the group's coordination depends on roles that no one has named, so newcomers cannot see how the work is divided and existing members cannot hand off cleanly.
    - Implicit hierarchy: undeclared seniority shapes who does what, while the project's official self-description claims peer equality.
